location.city_name: Santa Fe Animal Shelter & Humane Society

social_posts.post_text: I was visiting a church in Santa Fe and who should tap on my leg and ask me for help but this beautiful (and starving) dog. I asked around and the common consensus was that she had been dropped off and abandoned that morning. I got her into my rental car thanks to a jar of cinnamon peanut butter I just so happened to have with me. I considered keeping her but I knew the best thing for her was to take her to the Santa Fe Animal Shelter where she would get rehabilitation and a wonderful home. They've done an amazing job putting weight on her (and named her Delma which I love) and she's available for adoption now. #GoRescueADog
Happy birthday, Stamps. I hope you ate a lot of square cake. Thanks for being one of my best friends. I miss you and @mxkyegarrett more than I can say. Here's to Gene!
Happy birthday @maddielansbury! Always good to hang out with you in the mesa biome. #CubeSMP

Happy birthday to my friend, mentor, and found family member @pamlhouston. You are a force. Thank you for teaching me that a two-mile hike can always be turned into a six, that there's more to love in the world than fear, and to always, ALWAYS rent the convertible.

Update: Molly did well, and we're on our way home now. Thanks everyone for wishing her well!

Tldr: Molly is getting her tail cut off at the moment. She developed a small tumor in the last year -- I had it tested immediately and it was benign. It's not been bothering her, just oozing over all my furniture (a small price to pay for avoiding anesthesia at 13 years old). However, it recently ruptured and she is now at risk for developing an infection. And since there's barely any skin on the tail, they can't just cut off the tumor. And so, today she's joining the corgi club.
It's been quite the winter this year. ❄️

A winter for the books. Molly's tail did not make it, but we did. Yes, that's fireplace ash on my nose. I need a new furnace, many new gutters, and I still don't know how much water damage I'll be left with when it thaws, but the cabin roof held and I'm grateful for that.

location.city_name: Disney’s Hollywood Studios, Walt Disney World

social_posts.post_text:
Family reunion was in Orlando this year. 

#Hosted #AllTheDisneyThrills

Epcot and I are about the same age. A fact that was made clear after I rode the Guardians of the Galaxy coaster (listening to a song that is also nearly 40 years old) and then sat down on a bench between Japan and Morocco and threw out my back. Steroid shot aside, this is still one of my favorite places in the world. #Hosted #AllTheDisneyThrills

I've spent countless hours in Bookcraft with these three but never all together in person. Finally meeting PDawg was the cherry on top of this trip. I can't express how happy taking this photo made me. "Go read a book."

I had an amazing time at Disney World. I got to go to a TRON party after the park closed and also had time to see my incredible friends. I realized I am now a geriatric influencer (in many ways), but that’s okay.

I was over the moon meeting @pagingmrmorrow — I’ve watched so many of his videos and he was the reason I knew to rent a boat and cruise around the Seven Seas Lagoon!

Thank you again to @disneyparks and all the team members who made this trip happen for me. I won’t soon forget it and I’m already planning my next trip back.

#Hosted #AllTheDisneyThrills

Smug Pip and the fur he has been donating to birds at the cabin.
40 years young.

Today marks five years the earth has made do without the kindest person I've ever known, my dear grandmother, existing on it. And as for me, five years of grief and healing from the trauma of her decline. She had a series of strokes and suffered greatly for almost two months, unable to use her body or communicate in the ways she used to. Terribleness, as she would put it. I wouldn't wish end of life care (for the person dying or the person providing the care) on my worst enemy. She endured a hundred small cruelties by the hospital system, rehabilitation center staff, and unprepared family members. I know there are good people at rehab centers, but my grandmother was unlucky and the way we allow our elderly to die in this country is astounding.

I have wonderful memories and a lifetime of her love to fall back on, but this experience changed the way I see the world and made it hard to do my job that I love. I've been lucky to be supported by the people who watch my videos and buy my books. I've gotten help, and I am privileged to be able to aggressively chase ways to remember her daily -- making jam, planting flowers, writing someone a letter, cooking eggs the way she did, decorating a room in my house to remind me of her, buying the same washer and dryer she had so I can hear the same "laundry's done" song I used to hear at her house, and tracking down a second-hand rocking chair like the one she owned (this list took a turn towards unhinged, didn't it).

Anyway, if you're still reading and you have an elderly family member, please call them. Love you forever, Nan.
The happiest camper. Give Molly a comfy place to lounge (or a wood bench) and give me a Michael Crichton book and we're good to go.
Glacier never disappoints.

This year I'm thankful for my health. For physical safety. For National Rent-a-Fence. And for the fact that all the stripes and wide leg jeans and Sambas I wore when I was 13 in 1996 are back in style.
Some people have friends they like to visit in the city and some people have their favorite townhouse that they've stalked on Google Maps.
It's good to be a Celiac in NYC. Kidding. But Modern Bread and Bagel and Noglu made it bearable.

I don't care if you stopped watching my videos 7 years ago, come give me a hug.
